<h2>
    Best Time to Fish for Winter Steelhead
</h2>
<h3>
    Peak Months and Water Conditions
</h3>
<p>
    The winter steelhead run typically peaks between mid-December and late February. Ideal water levels are slightly colored with a moderate flow — after a good rain but before the rivers blow out.
</p>
<h3>
    Weather Considerations
</h3>
<p>
    Cold, wet weather is the norm. Dress in layers, use waterproof outerwear, and always check the forecast. Many anglers track weather and river conditions using apps like NOAA Weather Radar Live and RiverFlows.
</p>
<h2>
    Fishing Techniques for Winter Steelhead
</h2>
<h3>
    Drift Fishing
</h3>
<p>
    This traditional method involves bouncing bait along the riverbed. It’s especially effective in medium-speed water with rocky bottoms.
</p>
<h3>
    Bobber and Jig
</h3>
<p>
    One of the most beginner-friendly techniques, this involves suspending a jig under a bobber. Easy to cast and ideal for fishing from the bank.
</p>
<h3>
    Plunking
</h3>
<p>
    Set up on a riverbank with bait anchored in fast water. This passive method is great for fishing high water conditions.
</p>
<h3>
    Fly Fishing
</h3>
<p>
    Though challenging, swinging flies for winter steelhead is deeply rewarding. Use sink-tip lines and large intruder-style patterns in bright or contrasting colors.
</p>
