</p>
<h2>
    Essential Gear and Tackle for Steelhead
</h2>
<h3>
    Rods and Reels
</h3>
<p>
    For winter steelhead, a medium to medium-heavy spinning or baitcasting rod between 8.5 to 10 feet in length is ideal. The added length helps with casting and controlling drifts in larger rivers.
</p>
<p>
    Pair your rod with a smooth, high-drag-capacity reel. Spinning reels are great for beginners, while baitcasters offer superior control for seasoned anglers.
</p>
<h3>
    Lines and Leaders
</h3>
<p>
    Use a 10–15 lb test mainline for most river conditions, with a 6–12 lb fluorocarbon leader to maintain stealth. Monofilament lines offer stretch and shock absorption, while braided lines give superior sensitivity.
</p>
<h3>
    Recommended Baits and Lures
</h3>
<p>
    Steelhead are known for their aggression, especially in winter. Here are some proven options:
</p>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Natural baits</strong>: Cured salmon eggs, nightcrawlers, or sand shrimp.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Artificial lures</strong>: Pink worms, spinners (like Blue Fox or Panther Martin), and soft beads.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Jigs</strong>: Marabou or rubber jigs fished under a float.
    </li>
</ul>
<p>
    Pro Tip: Change colors frequently to match water clarity and fish mood — pink, chartreuse, orange, and white are top producers.
</p>
