    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    Wading Tips and Hazards
</h3>
<p>
    Always test depth and current with a wading staff before stepping forward. Avoid deep or fast-moving water and never wade alone in icy conditions.
</p>
<h3>
    Emergency Preparedness
</h3>
<p>
    Bring a dry bag with extra clothes, a first-aid kit, and a fully charged phone or GPS unit. In remote areas, a personal locator beacon (PLB) is highly recommended.
</p>
<h2>
    Steelhead Behavior in Winter
</h2>
<h3>
    How Water Temperature Affects Bites
</h3>
<p>
    Steelhead slow down in cold water (below 42°F), becoming less aggressive. They often hold in slower pools and deeper runs. Midday sun can warm up the bite window — plan your fishing accordingly.
</p>
<h3>
    Holding Zones and Structures
</h3>
<p>
    Look for:
</p>
<ul>
    <li>
        Tailouts of deep pools
    </li>
    <li>
        Edges of current seams
    </li>
    <li>
        Behind large rocks or logs
    </li>
    <li>
        Undercut banks
    </li>
</ul>
<p>
    Patience and accurate casting are key — steelhead won’t move far in winter but will strike if bait passes right in front of them.
</p>
